            <div type="commentary">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p>Rectangular slab of marble rounded at the top and sides, broken at the upper left
                    hand corner. It is darkened by a nail hole (by which the epitaph was originally
                    attached to the wall of the columbaria (Wilson, 1914, 119)) and remaining nail
                    on the middle right side, affecting the ends of lines 2 and 3. The face is
                    affected by weathering, showing discoloration. The measurements are 19.3 X 28.5
                    X 3.6 cm. It is a funerary verse written in elegiac couplets to a female child
                    (Soteris). There is one column and 6 lines, with even lines indented as a poetic
                    convention to demonstrate the meter. While the text is well centered on the
                    titulum, the spacing between lines is irregular (ranging from 2-1 cm) and there
                    is notable space between the last line and the edge of the stone (4 cm, whereas
                    only 2 cm from the top of the stone to the first line). The letters decrease in
                    size down the rows of text. </p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p>“Behold, under this inscription the bones of Soteris are located, having been
                    consumed by merciless death, she lies in a tomb. She had not yet completed six
                    years of life, when she was ordered to enter into the home of <ref
                        target="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C4%ABs_Pater">Black Dis</ref>. Those
                    tears which the mother ought to surrender to her daughter, those same tears her
                    daughter suddenly surrendered to her mother.”</p>
            </div>

